postcontent:
Selling my brand new unused never opened spikes tactical 13.2 BAR rail. I bought this awhile back directly from spikes tactical but ended up selling my rifle before i ever installed or opened it. I paid $250 plus shipping so i'm asking for at least $200.

The Spike's Tactical LW BAR2 - 13.2” Rail is a 1pc free floating quad-rail that’s machined from 6061-T6 Aluminum with a barrel nut machined from 7075-T6 Aluminum and finished in type III Hardcoat Anodizing on the rail and barrel nut. The main benefit of the BAR rail is to those who wish to have a suppressor inside of the rail or for those shooters who have large bear paw hands and who feel that skinnier rails are just too small ( the BAR is about the same circumference as a DD rail with the popular Magpul XTM covers). 

Inside dimensions 1.80" Outside dimensions Picatinny to picatinny 2.42" 

The BAR rail also features scalloping on the rails that not only saves a little bit more weight but also allows you to run this rail without any rail covers! This sounds like an outlandish claim to those who have had their hands cut up on other quad-rails that have been lovingly called “cheese graters”. The BAR also offers excellent heat ventilation, built in anti-rotation tabs to keep the rail and even the barrel nut from coming loose, and of course; sexy styling. 

But wait, there’s more! The BAR has 5 built in QD sockets (sling attachment points), allows for a continuous top rail, it’s compatible with many low profile gas blocks, and it’s made right here in the USA and backed by our LIFETIME WARRANTY!

title: For Sale:  ANTIQUE FOWLER, CIRCA 1845-1850. EXCELLENT CONDITION – Firing Condition
postcontent:
Antique Fowler, circa 1845-1850, excellent overall shape and in firing condition.

Percussion, nicely engraved lock, trigger guard and hammer, nice wood checkering.  

Nice inlaid breech with an approximately 40 inch barrel and an overall length of about 56 inches.  Smooth-bore of 18-20 gauge.

Wood is walnut and is excellent overall...in good sound condition.  Brass nose piece on end of stock, nice patina.

Lock is tight and functions correctly with no looseness.  Barrel is part octagon and round.  Beautiful patina to all metal – a delightful antique from a long ago era. 

Entire piece is in remarkable preserved condition and is shootable.  Believed to have been made in Belgium some 165+/- years ago.

I have personally fired this antique and it operated and fired just splendidly.  I will include a supply of paper wads and some shot as well as some percussion caps with a powder and shot measure.

Handles nice and looks beautiful on display on a wall or above a fireplace mantle.

This was evidently an expensive firearm back in 1845-1850 and used as a Fowler (bird hunting longer range hunting piece).

Here is history one can hold in your hands and is still in operable and usable condition.  Pre 1898 so not subject to federal firearms regulations.  

Reasonable offers will be considered.  Please email to arrange to inspect for purchase, or for additional photos.

title: For Sale/Trade:  80% Arms EZ Jig
postcontent:
The Easy Jig™ is a patented device that makes machining your 80% lower easier, faster, and safer. Lowers finished with the Easy Jig™ have a better finish and hold tolerances that could not be achieved using any other jig on the market today. You do not need to own a drill press or mill to use the Easy Jig™. It truly makes finishing your lower a monkey simple process. On top of all this, it’s extremely durable and can be reused for dozens of lowers.

This version of the AR-15 Universal Easy Jig™ is ONLY compatible with AR-15 80% Lowers.

Easy Jig™ highlights:

Easier
Built in drill/end-mill depth gauge for the trigger and rear-shelf pockets (patent pending)
Eliminates the need for expensive measurement tools
Quick verification of depth setting – eliminates slippage issues that can ruin parts
Eliminates constant measuring to determine depth while milling
Safer
End-mill downward force can’t separate the drill press taper chuck
It is safer to move router by hand than to move the jig around on a drill press

Uses Common Hand Tools
The Easy Jig™ is designed to hold tolerances using a common hand-drill
No drill press is required, milling is done with a router
Routers are much more portable than a drill press, easily borrowed from a friend
Routers are made for cutting pockets using a template
Routers are cheaper than a drill press.
Faster
Pocket drilling requires 10 holes drilled once – Traditional jigs require 42 holes to be drilled once, precisely aligned and clamped, then re-drilled to a larger diameter
Trigger pocket can be cut in 6 to 11 passes vs 25 passes required with a drill press
Router cuts pockets 5-6x faster
Hand-drilling the trigger group/safety selector holes is faster to setup
Lower can be completed in 1 hour (instead of 3 hours for the old drill press method)
Durable
The Easy Jig™ can be used to make dozens of lowers
Components are Type III hard anodized for extra wear resistance. Lost 5/32 bit, but its a $4 drill bit at home depot. Asking $145, paid 150 for the jig and $45 for the bits. Used once, like new. Would cost you $200+ new with shipping. Need $$ for parts and price is firm at $140. Open to ammo trades too, 5.56 or 9mm Luger/parabellum (no +p, +p+ 9mm ammo) will trade for 200 rounds 5.56 and 100 rounds Luger blazer brass; or cheap revolver or pocket pistol, doesn't hurt to ask.

title: For Sale:  Marlin Glenfield Model 60 22LR semi auto with scope GREAT SHAPE!
postcontent:
Im an FFL so I can handle all the paperwork if youre local. I can also ship it to a dealer in your state.

This is a sweet model 60 I took in trade. Basically its a semi auto 22lr with a nice scope. This is a collectable early model with the micro rifling and the 17 round tube. Shoots great, super accurate. I posted more detailed info from wiki below. Check it out. ;) 

The Marlin Model 60 was developed in 1960 from the Model 99 design. The primary difference was that the stock was made of birch instead of walnut to reduce the recurring production costs for the more expensive wood. Marlin also moved away from their practice of using steel inner tubes with their tubular magazine. They moved back to brass inner tubes as other companies had done. This, instead of the steel tubes often seen on earlier Marlin .22 rifles, completely eliminated the rust problems that the all-steel tubular magazines had experienced which helped make the inexpensive Marlin rifle as durable as more expensive .22 caliber rifles. The Model 60 additionally featured a 16-groove rifled barrel, utilizing Marlin's trademarked Micro-Groove rifling technology, which had been developed in 1953. This rifling, with its precision-crowned muzzle, gave the Model 60 an inherent, enhanced accuracy over competing rifles, which used traditional deep grooved rifling, because the bullet was not as severely deformed while traveling down the barrel, and downrange.

The Model 60 has a manual "fully open" bolt hold position, activated by pushing the charging handle inwards towards the gun when it is in the fully retracted, open breech position. To close the bolt with the manual bolt hold-open engaged, the charging handle must be pulled out, away from the gun, before the bolt will go forward.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Chinese AK with no import marks.
postcontent:
Low 5 digit serial number, no prefix.
All matching parts.

The only things that are stamped on this AK are: 
"MADE IN CHINA BY NORINCO" on the bottom of the receiver just in front of the mag well (but no Norinco star),
"CAL 7.62 X 39MM" & "SEMI-AUTO" on the left side of the receiver,
a "6" on the front side of the front sight a-frame, 
half of a "6" on the barrel covered by the handguard
a "7" on the top of the front trunnion covered by the dust cover. 
(From my research those numbers are the factories that the parts were made at in China.)

I've taken this gun apart and there are no other stamps or areas that stamps were scratched off anywhere. 
Has small scuff on left side of receiver on the "SEMI-AUTO" stamp (looks to be scuffed at factory before it was blued).
Comes with 3 steel mags and 3 Tapco mags.

I don't know much about Pre MAK-90 CHICOM AK's but I've seen similar Chinese AK's sell anywhere from $1100-$2800
This one is a solid 90% or better.

I'm open to any info anyone may have on this rifle. 
Or make an offer.
